<!DOCTYPE MAN SYSTEM "../../man.dtd">
<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE>poly  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE>April 1993  </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="poly"> polynomial definition  </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[p]=poly(a,&quot;x&quot;, [&quot;flag&quot;])  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>a  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : matrix or real number
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>x  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : symbolic variable
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>&quot;flag&quot;  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
    : string (&quot;roots&quot;, &quot;coeff&quot;), default value is &quot;roots&quot;.
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    If <VERB>a</VERB> is a matrix, <VERB>p</VERB> is the characteristic polynomial i.e.
     <VERB>determinant(x*eye()-a)</VERB>, <VERB>x</VERB> being the symbolic variable.
  </P>
  <P>
    If <VERB>v</VERB>  is a vector, <VERB>poly(v,&quot;x&quot;,[&quot;roots&quot;])</VERB>  is the polynomial
    with <VERB>roots</VERB> the entries of <VERB>v</VERB> and <VERB>&quot;x&quot;</VERB> as formal variable.
    (In this case,  <VERB>roots</VERB> and   <VERB>poly</VERB> are inverse functions).
  </P>
  <P>
    <VERB>poly(v,&quot;x&quot;,&quot;coeff&quot;)</VERB> creates the polynomial with symbol <VERB>&quot;x&quot;</VERB>
    and with coefficients the entries of <VERB>v</VERB> (v(1) is the constant term of the polynomial). (Here <VERB>poly</VERB> and <VERB>coeff</VERB>
    are inverse functions).
  </P>
  <P>
    <VERB>s=poly(0,&quot;s&quot;)</VERB> is the seed for defining polynomials with symbol
    <VERB>&quot;s&quot;</VERB>.
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
s=poly(0,"s");p=1+s+2*s^2;
A=rand(2,2);poly(A,"x")
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
